  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT286-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">1. irantu piṉṉiṉṟa kiḻavaṉ kuṟaimaṟāmal kūṟiyatu. 2. pāṅkaṟkuc
          colliyatūumām. </p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">1. Spoken about [the confidante's?] not refusing [his]
          request by HIM who implored [her]. 2. Spoken to the companion. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT286">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l> uḷḷik kāṇpeṉ pōlvaṉ muḷḷeyiṟ</l>
          <l> ṟamiḻta mūṟumañ cevvāyk kamaḻaki</l>
          <l> lāra nāṟu maṟalpōṟ kūntaṟ</l>
          <l> pēramar maḻaikkaṇ maṭantai</l>
          <l> mūraṉ muṟuvaloṭu mataiiya nōkkē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l>Remembering, I seem to see</l>
          <l>the playful look together with the smiling smile <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> mūral muṟuval </term>: again a synonym compound with intensifying intention? Or is this even a figura etymologica (the DEDR has both in one lemma, 5687)?  </note> </l>
          <l rend="indent2">of the girl with big beautiful <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> pēr amar maḻai kaṇ </term>: or "with very beautiful rain eyes".   </note> rain eyes,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">tresses like black sand, smelling of sandal [and] fragrant</l>
          <l rend="indent8">with eagle wood <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> kamaḻ akil </term>: how to understand the syntax here? Is this a chiastic structure <term xml:lang="ta"> kamaḻ akil – āra nāṟum </term>, in which both are to be construed with <term xml:lang="ta"> kūntal </term>? Or is it "smelling of sandal [and] fragrant eagle wood"?    </note> ,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">pretty red mouth with ambrosia seeping from thorn[-like] teeth.</l>


        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
  </text>
